<div id="review_3712939412" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3712939412" />
    <a title="George Rodger" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/88147086-george-rodger"><img alt="George Rodger" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3712939412?book_show_action=true">Dec 29, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="George Rodger" class="user" itemprop="url" name="George Rodger" href="/user/show/88147086-george-rodger">George Rodger</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/12250856-chasing-the-devil">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3712939412" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8326035253805480722">I bought the book because I was doing some research for a university assignment- on Sierra Leone. I enjoyed the book but eventually could see that most of the book covered the Liberia end of the trek he describes. I’ve visited both countries and much prefer Salone. Liberia, when I visited, seemed a much more menacing place. I remember going to Robertsfield beach and seeing the priceless sweep of the sand and palm trees. The sort of place that hotels and tourism could transform. I asked how far t</span>
  <span id="freeText8326035253805480722" style="display:none">I bought the book because I was doing some research for a university assignment- on Sierra Leone. I enjoyed the book but eventually could see that most of the book covered the Liberia end of the trek he describes. I’ve visited both countries and much prefer Salone. Liberia, when I visited, seemed a much more menacing place. I remember going to Robertsfield beach and seeing the priceless sweep of the sand and palm trees. The sort of place that hotels and tourism could transform. I asked how far the beach went and was told 200 miles. Whether it’s ingrained in Liberia’s recent history, I don’t know but I could never see the country having a peaceful and fulfilling future. Somebody will kick over the anthill whenever it looks like it’s going to be successful. Sierra Leone was rescued by the British who managed to curtail Foday Sankohs murderous activities. The Brits still felt some responsibility. Liberia has no big brother to come to their aid. Companies will come, extract their iron ore and magnificent forestry and leave but no one but the Lebanese will try to build a life there. And their connection will ultimately only be a commercial one. Perhaps it’s the devil worshipping societies, which I’d never heard of, that are too powerful? The book was interesting but I couldn’t see it exciting interest in a readership that had no African interest. It didn’t have the scope of the Congo book. Still, rancid food, no lights, bilharzia, guinea worm. What’s not to like? At least the mango flies stayed away and weren’t laying their eggs in his shirts. Where next Tim?<br />GDR.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8326035253805480722" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


