<div id="review_2010772478" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2010772478" />
    <a title="SWZIE" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/57844534-swzie"><img alt="SWZIE" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1495572288p2/57844534.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2010772478?book_show_action=true">Jul 16, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="SWZIE" class="user" itemprop="url" name="SWZIE" href="/user/show/57844534-swzie">SWZIE</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780099532064" href="/book/show/15733135-chasing-the-devil">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2010772478" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14409333700341689086">The prologue of ‘Chasing the Devil’ was the appetizer that stimulated me to buy the book. In the introduction, Tim Butcher’s audacious decision to ignore the advice of his trusted local guide and use an unknown temporary guide, in the lawless hinterland of Liberia, piqued my interest. His seemingly reckless venture through dense labyrinthine jungle - overwhelmed with trepidation – that the man leading the trail, may have belonged to one of the notorious gangs known for their violence and ritual </span>
  <span id="freeText14409333700341689086" style="display:none">The prologue of ‘Chasing the Devil’ was the appetizer that stimulated me to buy the book. In the introduction, Tim Butcher’s audacious decision to ignore the advice of his trusted local guide and use an unknown temporary guide, in the lawless hinterland of Liberia, piqued my interest. His seemingly reckless venture through dense labyrinthine jungle - overwhelmed with trepidation – that the man leading the trail, may have belonged to one of the notorious gangs known for their violence and ritual killings – and was possibly leading him to an ambush – tantalised me. Butcher’s fear proved unfounded, but it was an exciting precursor to the full story of the author’s thrilling adventure: first through Sierra Leon – then a gruelling journey on foot, through Liberia and Guinea, during, which, Butcher and his three companions showed admirable endurance.<br /> <br />Tim Butcher, inspired by Graham Greene, followed his footsteps into some not easily accessible areas of Africa. Throughout the book he compares his journey with Green’s – and imparts his knowledge of political and historical facts. It appears that nothing much has changed in that region of Liberia since Greene’s journey seventy four years previously. Whereas Graham Greene in 1935 was accompanied by his cousin Barbara, Tim Butcher had an Englishman (David), and two natives, Johnson and Mr Omaru. The latter eventually opened up to Butcher and confided personal details about his past. This was an example of the incredible bond and trust, which gradually developed, between the travel companions.<br /> <br />By the time they reached a village called Kpangbalamai, I became thoroughly engrossed in the book. I’m an avid reader of travel books where I’m taken on a virtual journey; the author gave me a feel of what the country is like with its smell, sounds and sights. He described the impoverished people’s daily struggle for survival. I could visualise the native’s day to day life: crushing palm kernels, smoking river shrimp, knotting rattan tree-climbing belts, spinning cotton and weaving fishing nets etc. I could imagine the scene through Tim’s eyes: there were the same mud huts as Greene described; rice birds busily making nests that hung from bare branches - the dusty village surrounded by jungle vegetation - bananas and cotton trees etc. <br /><br />It’s an illuminating compelling book, pact with anecdotes and facts. For instance, I found it ironic that the former slaves, Americo-Liberians, who settled in Liberia and became the ruling class, disgracefully used forced labour themselves. Greene’s own journey recounted in his book ‘Journey Without Maps’, was actually backed by British anti-slavery campaigners. The interior of Liberia wasn’t even mapped back then. The author explained that ‘Journey Without Maps’ was banned mostly for exposing the corrupt officials who were exploiting the native population.<br /><br />The book describes a lawless, unstable country, left in ruins after its brutal history: a succession of civil wars, a coup, violent retributions and gruesome killings in lurid detail. <br /> <br />I was fascinated by the dark tales of the bush secret societies. The belief in spiritualism and the devil are deeply ingrained in the culture of these people. Initiation into the secret societies sounds bizarre and incredible, but so intriguing. The people are afraid to discuss these secret societies, so knowledge of what takes place is very limited.<br /><br />The macabre tales of ritualistic killings by the Heart Men sounds revolting. Rooted in their religious ideology, they believed they could acquire the strength of others through eating their vital organs. Ritualistic killings involving cannibalism apparently still continues in Liberia.<br /><br />I had perfunctory acknowledged that the job of a foreign correspondent was often risky and dangerous, but Tim’s account of how two of his friends, fellow journalists, were killed in a rebel ambush, accentuated my awareness of how brave these men are.<br /> <br />The book has snippets of information in abundance; I’ve highlighted just a few pieces, which captured my attention. It’s very well written; highly recommended. Blood River, by the same author, is also a well deserved best seller.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14409333700341689086" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


